**Sec. 70501. Termination of Previously-Owned Clean Vehicle Credit**  
This section amends Section 25E(g) to shorten the expiration date for the previously-owned clean vehicle credit from December 31, 2032, to September 30, 2025. The change applies to taxpayers claiming the credit for qualifying used electric or fuel cell vehicles purchased after September 30, 2025. It effectively ends the credit for used clean vehicles after that date, impacting consumers and dealers relying on the incentive.

**Sec. 70502. Termination of Clean Vehicle Credit**  
This section modifies Section 30D(h) to replace the previous deadline of December 31, 2032, with a new cutoff of September 30, 2025, for qualifying new clean vehicles. It also removes outdated subclauses (iv) and (v) from Section 30D(e)(1)(B) and (2)(B), streamlining the credit’s eligibility rules. The change applies to vehicles placed in service after September 30, 2025, affecting manufacturers and buyers of new electric and fuel cell cars.

**Sec. 70503. Termination of Qualified Commercial Clean Vehicles Credit**  
This section amends Section 45W(g) to shorten the expiration date for the commercial clean vehicle credit from December 31, 2032, to September 30, 2025. It targets businesses purchasing or leasing clean delivery trucks, heavy-duty vans, and other commercial electric vehicles. The change ends the credit for qualifying commercial vehicles acquired after September 30, 2025.

**Sec. 70504. Termination of Alternative Fuel Vehicle Refueling Property Credit**  
This section amends Section 30C(i) to replace the expiration date of December 31, 2032, with June 30, 2026, for the alternative fuel vehicle refueling property credit. It applies to taxpayers installing electric vehicle charging stations or hydrogen refueling infrastructure. The change shortens the window for claiming the credit by about six months, impacting infrastructure investments.

**Sec. 70505. Termination of Energy Efficient Home Improvement Credit**  
This section amends Section 25C(h) to shift the expiration date for the energy-efficient home improvement credit from December 31, 2032, to December 31, 2025. It also updates the efficiency criteria for oil furnaces and hot water boilers to require compliance with 2021 Energy Star standards and a minimum of 20% eligible fuel blends. The change applies to improvements placed in service after December 31, 2025, affecting homeowners and contractors.

**Sec. 70506. Termination of Residential Clean Energy Credit**  
This section amends Section 25D(h) to replace the previous expiration date of December 31, 2034, with a cutoff based on expenditure dates, specifically December 31, 2025. It removes paragraphs (4) and (5) of Section 25D(g), which previously outlined phase-down schedules for the credit. The change applies to expenditures made after December 31, 2025, impacting homeowners installing solar, wind, or geothermal systems.

**Sec. 70507. Termination of Energy Efficient Commercial Buildings Deduction**  
This section adds a new subsection (i) to Section 179D, terminating the deduction for energy-efficient commercial buildings for construction that begins after June 30, 2026. It applies to new commercial buildings or renovations where the construction start date exceeds this threshold. The change affects architects, developers, and contractors planning large commercial projects after mid-2026.

**Sec. 70508. Termination of New Energy Efficient Home Credit**  
This section amends Section 45L(h) to shorten the expiration date for the new energy-efficient home credit from December 31, 2032, to June 30, 2026. It applies to qualifying new homes built to meet specific energy efficiency standards. The change ends the credit for homes completed after June 30, 2026, impacting homebuilders and developers.

**Sec. 70509. Termination of Cost Recovery for Energy Property**  
This section amends Section 168(e)(3)(B)(vi) to remove the previous subclause (I) and redesignate subclauses (II) and (III) as (I) and (II). It eliminates the special depreciation allowance for energy property placed in service after December 31, 2024. The change affects taxpayers claiming accelerated depreciation on energy-efficient equipment or renewable energy installations.

**Sec. 70510. Modifications of Zero-Emission Nuclear Power Production Credit**  
This section adds new restrictions under Section 45U(c)(3) to deny the zero-emission nuclear power production credit to taxpayers that are specified foreign entities or foreign-influenced entities. It applies to taxable years beginning after the date of enactment. The change targets foreign entities with ties to adversarial nations, restricting access to nuclear energy tax incentives.

**Sec. 70511. Termination of Clean Hydrogen Production Credit**  
This section amends Section 45V(c)(3)(C) to replace the expiration date for the clean hydrogen production credit from January 1, 2033, to January 1, 2028. It applies to taxpayers producing hydrogen using eligible technologies. The change shortens the credit’s lifespan by five years, impacting hydrogen infrastructure and production projects.

**Sec. 70512. Termination and Restrictions on Clean Electricity Production Credit**  
This section imposes a hard cutoff for wind and solar facilities placed in service after December 31, 2027, under Section 45Y(d)(4). It also restricts eligibility for facilities receiving material assistance from prohibited foreign entities, as defined in Section 7701(a)(52). Additionally, it denies credits to taxpayers with foreign-influenced entities or specified foreign entities. The changes apply to taxable years beginning after the date of enactment, targeting wind and solar developers with foreign ties.

**Sec. 70513. Termination and Restrictions on Clean Electricity Investment Credit**  
This section limits the clean electricity investment credit under Section 48E for wind and solar facilities placed in service after December 31, 2027. It also restricts eligibility for facilities with material assistance from prohibited foreign entities and denies credits to taxpayers with foreign-influenced entities. It introduces recapture rules for applicable payments to prohibited foreign entities and applies to taxable years beginning after the date of enactment, affecting wind and solar investors.

**Sec. 70514. Phase-Out and Restrictions on Advanced Manufacturing Production Credit**  
This section phases out the advanced manufacturing production credit for applicable critical minerals after December 31, 2030, with complete phase-out by 2033. It terminates the credit for wind energy components after December 31, 2027, and for metallurgical coal after December 31, 2029. It also restricts eligibility for taxpayers with foreign-influenced entities or specified foreign entities. The changes apply to taxable years beginning after the date of enactment, impacting domestic mineral and component manufacturers.

**Sec. 70515. Restriction on the Extension of Advanced Energy Project Credit Program**  
This section amends Section 48C(e)(3)(C) to prohibit increases in the qualified investment amount for the advanced energy project credit program. It applies to projects where construction begins after the date of enactment. The change limits federal support for large-scale energy projects, affecting developers and investors relying on enhanced credits.

**Sec. 70521. Extension and Modification of Clean Fuel Production Credit**  
This section restricts the clean fuel production credit to fuels derived exclusively from feedstocks produced in the U.S., Mexico, or Canada. It prohibits negative emission rates and requires adjustments for indirect land use changes. It extends the credit’s expiration to December 31, 2029, and adds reporting requirements for sustainable aviation fuel. The changes apply to fuel produced after December 31, 2025, impacting biofuel producers and refiners.

**Sec. 70522. Restrictions on Carbon Oxide Sequestration Credit**  
This section adds new restrictions under Section 45Q(f)(10) to deny the carbon oxide sequestration credit to taxpayers that are specified foreign entities or foreign-influenced entities. It also modifies the credit’s applicability to exclude certain uses and utilizations. The changes apply to taxable years beginning after the date of enactment, targeting carbon capture projects with foreign involvement.

**Sec. 70523. Intangible Drilling and Development Costs Taken into Account for Purposes of Computing Adjusted Financial Statement Income**  
This section amends Section 56A(c)(13) to require taxpayers to reduce deductions for intangible drilling and development costs by depreciation and depletion expenses claimed on financial statements. It applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025, affecting oil and gas producers reporting under GAAP or IFRS.

**Sec. 70524. Income from Hydrogen Storage, Carbon Capture, Advanced Nuclear, Hydropower, and Geothermal Energy Added to Qualifying Income of Certain Publicly Traded Partnerships**  
This section expands the definition of qualifying income under Section 7704(d)(1)(E) to include income from hydrogen storage, carbon capture, advanced nuclear, hydropower, and geothermal energy. It applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025, allowing publicly traded partnerships in these sectors to qualify for pass-through taxation.

**Sec. 70525. Allow for Payments to Certain Individuals Who Dye Fuel**  
This section creates a new Section 6435 to allow payments to individuals who remove indelibly dyed diesel fuel or kerosene for exempt uses. It applies to fuel removed on or after 180 days after enactment. The change provides a refund mechanism for dyed fuel users, impacting farmers, fishermen, and off-road vehicle operators. [end of text]


